[3] South East Asia
Date: Tue 10 Aug 2021
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/08/parts-southeast-asia-still-heat-delta-battles


Parts of South East Asia are still grappling with high COVID-19 activity, with Thailand today [Tue 10 Aug 2021] reporting a record daily high for deaths and Viet Nam still reporting high daily totals.

Thailand today [Tue 10 Aug 2021] reported nearly 20 000 cases, with a record single-day high for deaths at 235, according to Nikkei Asia (https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Coronavirus/Thailand-scrambles-for-COVID-19-antiviral-as-vaccines-run-short). Bangkok is currently the country's epicenter, and some experts worry that Thailand's cases haven't peaked yet. The country's vaccine rollout has been rocky, and Thailand's pharmacy trade group has warned the health ministry about possible shortages of the antiviral drug, favipiravir.

Thailand is receiving USD 5 million in aid from the US government to help in its battle with COVID-19, Ned Price, a State Department spokesman, said yesterday [Mon 9 Aug 2021] on Twitter (https://twitter.com/StateDeptSpox/status/1425075681038323713). He also noted that the United States is providing USD 50 million for Myanmar, which is also experiencing a humanitarian crisis complicated by a virus surge.

Viet Nam is still reporting high daily case numbers, with 9323 new infections reported yesterday [Mon 9 Aug 2021], according to VN Express (https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/vietnam-adds-9-323-cases-to-covid-19-tally-4338111.html). The main hot spots are Ho Chi Minh City, followed by 2 provinces in southern Viet Nam, Binh Duong and Dong Nai.

In other South East Asia developments, some countries are phasing out China's Sinovac vaccines due to concerns that they are less effective than other vaccines, according to the Washington Post (https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/covid-vaccines-delta-china-asia/2021/08/10/24d0df60-f664-11eb-a636-18cac59a98dc_story.html). For example, in the middle of July [2021], Thailand announced a plan to mix doses, giving people who had received their 1st dose of Sinovac a 2nd dose of AstraZeneca-Oxford vaccine. And health workers fully vaccinated with Sinovac are receiving a 3rd booster dose of AstraZeneca or one of the 2 mRNA vaccines. Cambodia's government said it will offer AstraZeneca booster shots to those who received 2 Sinovac doses.

In early June [2021], WHO announced emergency listing for Sinovac, and Chinese officials recently announced that the country will donate 2 billion vaccine doses this year [2021], along with USD 100 million to support COVAX activities.

[byline: Lisa Schnirring]

